  "prompt": "Is it correct to use the phrase \"revert back\" in a sentence? I hear it all the time and on occasion even on BBC!",
  "response": "The phrase \"revert back\" is commonly used, but it is technically redundant. The word **\"revert\"** itself means *to return to a previous state or condition*, so adding **\"back\"** is unnecessary. For example:\n\n- **Incorrect:** \"Please revert back to me with your feedback.\"  \n- **Correct:** \"Please revert to me with your feedback.\"  \n- **Alternatively:** \"Please get back to me with your feedback.\"\n\nThat said, \"revert back\" is widely used in informal communication, and its redundancy is often overlooked in casual contexts. However, in formal writing or speech, it\u2019s best to avoid the redundancy and use \"revert\" alone.",
